= Joan Westmoreland\n|alma_mater   = [[Georgia State University]]\n|religion     = [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]]\n}}\n'''Leon Acton''' \"'''Lynn'''\" '''Westmoreland''' (born April 2, 1950) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|Georgia|3|}}, serving since 2005. The district, numbered as the {{ushr|Georgia|8}} during his first term, stretches from the far southern [[Atlanta]] suburbs to the suburbs of [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]]. He is a member of the [[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nWestmoreland was born in Atlanta, the son of Margaret Ferrell (n\u00e9e Lawson) and Leon Acton Westmoreland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/westmoreland.htm |title=Lynn Westmoreland |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref> He grew up in Metro Atlanta. He has no degree beyond a high school diploma. He attended [[Georgia State University]],but dropped out to work in a family construction business in which he later became an executive. He served in the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] from 1993 to 2005, rising to the position of House Republican Leader in 2001. He held that position until 2003 when he stepped down in order to devote time to his Congressional campaign in late 2003. He continued to serve in the Georgia House until his election to the US House in 2005.\n\nAs Republican Leader in the Georgia House, he led the fight against intense partisan [[gerrymandering]] during the redistricting process controlled by the Democratic majority in 2001. He abandoned his opposition and was instrumental in the mid-decade redistricting that took place in 2005, after Republicans won control of the Georgia legislature in the 2004 elections.<ref name=WashTimes>{{cite news |url=http://images.washtimes.com/national/20050225-111610-4014r.htm |title=Election districts drawing attention |publisher=The Washington Times |date=February 26, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101011854/http://images.washtimes.com/national/20050225-111610-4014r.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">[http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/20/us/20murphy.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107042244/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/20/us/20murphy.html |date=January 7, 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://times-georgian.com/view/full_story/3278580/article-Georgia--Carroll--Haralson-remember-Tom-Murphy ]{{dead link|date=April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring his first term in the [[109th United States Congress]], Westmoreland was appointed to the [[U.S. House Committee on Small Business]], [[U.S. House Committee on Government Reform]], and the [[U.S. House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}. In January 2015, the House Intelligence Committee was reorganized, and a subcommittee on Cybersecurity and the National Security Agency was created with Westmoreland appointed to be the subcommittee's first chairman.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/231044-spy-panel-shakeup-will-add-focus-on-cyber-cia | title=Spy panel shakeup will add focus on cyber, CIA | accessdate=2014-01-30 | last=Hattem| first=Julian  | date=2014-01-28 | work=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nAs a U.S. congressman, Westmoreland cosponsored a bill to place the [[Ten Commandments]] in the House of Representatives and the [[United States Senate|Senate]]. Westmoreland also sponsored a bill that the Ten Commandments could be displayed in courthouses in a historical setting.<ref name=11alive>{{cite news|url=http://www.11alive.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=43064|title=GOP Intros 10 Commandments Bill|agency=Associated Press}}{{dead link|date=December 2012}}</ref> In May 2006, political humorist [[Stephen Colbert]] interviewed Westmoreland for ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' show segment ''[[Better Know a District]]'', and during the interview, asked Westmoreland to name the Ten Commandments. Westmoreland was able to name only three of them.<ref name=cnn>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/TV/06/09/tv.stephencolbert.ap/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081105072150/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/TV/06/09/tv.stephencolbert.ap/index.html |date=November 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/22/business/fi-colbert22 |title=Running for office? Better run from Colbert \u2013 latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2006-10-22 |accessdate=2015-04-01 |first=Jim |last=Puzzanghera}}</ref> Govtrack.us ranked Westmoreland as tied for the most conservative member of the [[112th Congress]].\n\nWestmoreland led a group of congressmen who opposed the 2006 renewal of certain provisions in the [[Voting Rights Act]] that require nine Southern states and a number of counties (mostly in the South) to obtain Federal permission for certain changes to election law or changes in venue.  Westmoreland and his colleagues claimed that it was no longer fair to target their states, given the passage of time since 1965 and the changes their states had made to provide fair elections and voting.  Despite Westmoreland's objections, a strong bipartisan majority renewed the Voting Rights Act for another 25 years without changes.<ref name=\"cbsnews\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/14/ap/politics/mainD8IRNHO85.shtml|title=House Renews Voting Rights Act Unchanged|publisher=''CBS News''|accessdate=2008-08-29|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080427042841/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/14/ap/politics/mainD8IRNHO85.shtml|archivedate=2008-04-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Westmoreland ran unopposed in the Republican primary and was re-elected after defeating his Democratic opponent Stephen Camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.times-herald.com/local/Westmoreland-retains-seat-582222|title=Westmoreland retains seat|accessdate=2008-11-06|last=Pedraza-Vidamour|first=Brenda|date=2008-11-04|publisher=[[Newnan Times-Herald]]}}</ref> After his win, Westmoreland announced that he was considering running for the office of [[List of governors of Georgia|Governor of Georgia]] in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/gwinnett/content/metro/stories/2008/11/05/housega_incumbents.html |title=Georgia House incumbents win their races |accessdate=13 November 2008 |last=Smith |first=Ben |date=2008-11-05 |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |publisher= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629204223/http://www.ajc.com/gwinnett/content/metro/stories/2008/11/05/housega_incumbents.html |archivedate=June 29, 2009 }}</ref> but later indicated in an April 2009 press release that he would not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/metro/content/metro/stories/2009/04/24/westmoreland_georgia_governor.html?cxntlid=homepage_tab_newstab |title=Westmoreland won't run for governor |publisher=''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' |accessdate=2009-07-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629233019/http://www.ajc.com/metro/content/metro/stories/2009/04/24/westmoreland_georgia_governor.html?cxntlid=homepage_tab_newstab |archivedate=June 29, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Westmoreland signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2008/08/westmoreland.pdf |format=PDF |title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Lynn Westmoreland |publisher=Americansforprosperity.org |accessdate=2015-04-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219061216/http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax/ |archivedate=2015-02-19 |df= }}</ref>\n\nAs of February 4, 2016, Westmoreland has the most conservative ideology score of any member of the House of Representatives in the 114th Congress according to GovTrack.<ref>\"Analysis Methodology.\" GovTrack.us. Civic Impulse, 4 Feb. 2016. Web. 08 Feb. 2016. <https://www.govtrack.us/about/analysis#ideology>.\n</ref> As of April 25, 2016 he is the second most conservative member of the House.\n\n===Legislation===\n{{incomplete|section|date=February 2016}}\nWestmoreland has sponsored various bills of his own, including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Westmoreland's Legislation|url=http://www.congress.gov/member/lynn-westmoreland/1779?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22westmoreland%22%5D%2C%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====110th Congress (2007\u20132008)====\n* H.R. 3229, a bill to mint 350,000 $1 infantry coins for sale during 2012, with a surcharge of $10 on the sale of such coins, and with revenue to be allocated to the [[National Infantry Museum]], introduced July 30, 2007, signed into law October 8, 2008\n* H.R. 3492, a bill to increase the allowable amount of campaign contributions to political action committees (PACs), introduced September 6, 2007\n\n====112th Congress (2011\u20132012)====\n* H.R. 5710, a bill to establish a total daily energy consumption standard for medium temperature commercial refrigerators, introduced May 10, 2012\n\n====113th Congress (2013\u20132014)====\n* H.R. 3985, a bill to prohibit health insurers from making required payments under the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (PPACA) for transitional reinsurance in the individual health insurance market, and to repeal the PPACA's risk corridors and risk adjustments for insurance companies, introduced February 3, 2014\n* H.R. 4604, a bill to allow for consumers to opt out of having personally identifiable information collected by the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] (CFPB) and to set a 60-day time limit on how long the CFPB can store such information, introduced May 7, 2014\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit|Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity|Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity]]\n* '''[[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]]'''\n* [[House Select Committee on the Events Surrounding the 2012 Terrorist Attack in Benghazi]]\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]\n* [[Tea Party Caucus]]\n\n==Controversy==\nOn September 4, 2008, Westmoreland described [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] presidential nominee [[Barack Obama]] and his wife [[Michelle Obama|Michelle]] as \"[[wikt:uppity|uppity]]\", a pejorative considered by some as historically used to describe African-Americans who have made economic, social, or political progress.<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/la-oe-shipler16apr16,0,2335261.story |title=Racism's resonance |publisher=Latimes.com |date=1994-11-08 |accessdate=2015-04-01 |first=David K. |last=Shipler}}</ref> Westmoreland said to reporters, \"Just from what little I\u2019ve seen of her and Mr. Obama, Senator Obama, they're a member of an elitist-class individual that thinks that they're uppity.\" When asked to confirm his use of the word,  Westmoreland answered, \"Uppity, yeah.\"<ref name=\"HILL\">{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/leading-the-news/westmoreland-calls-obama-uppity-2008-09-04.html |title=News Archive |publisher=TheHill.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cqpolitics.com/cq-assets/cqmultimedia/audio/uppity.mp3|format=MP3|title=Audio recording of Rep. Westmoreland referring to Obamas as \"uppity\"|publisher=Cqpolitics.com|accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe ensuing media attention compelled Westmoreland to issue the following statement: \"I\u2019ve never heard that term used in a racially derogatory sense. It is important to note that the dictionary definition of 'uppity' is 'affecting an air of inflated self-esteem\u2014snobbish.' That's what we meant by uppity when we used it in the mill village where I grew up.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/washington/2008/09/rep-westmorelan.html|work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Top of the Ticket|date=September 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nDuring the national debate in 2015 over the future of the Confederate flag some Republicans proposed a moderate amendment to allow Confederate symbols at national cemeteries. Representative Lynn Westmoreland distinguished between racism and a memorial,<ref name=\"NYT_2015\">{{citation |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/10/us/republicans-back-down-on-confederate-flags-at-us-cemeteries.html?partner=socialflow&smid=tw-nytimes |publisher=New York Times |date=10 July 2015 |accessdate=10 July 2015 |title=Republicans Retreat as Confederate Flag Issue Roils Congress |authors= JENNIFER STEINHAUER and JONATHAN WEISMAN |location=Washington, DC}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"When you\u2019re putting a flag on someone\u2019s grave, to me it\u2019s a little different from being racist. It\u2019s more of a memorial... You can\u2019t make an excuse for things that happened, but the majority of people that actually died in the Civil War on the Confederate side did not own slaves. These were people that were fighting for their states. I don\u2019t think they had even any thoughts about slavery.\"|Representative Lynn Westmoreland July 2015}}\nWhen Westmoreland was asked if he understood Representative [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] perspective, he responded,\"I guess the question is, \u2018Does he understand where I\u2019m coming from?\"<ref name=\"NYT_2015\" />\n\n==Political campaigns==\nWestmoreland won a plurality of votes in the Republican primary election in 2004, but faced fellow Republican Dylan Glenn in a runoff. Westmoreland received 55.5% of the vote in the runoff. The district was so heavily Republican that Westmoreland's primary victory was [[tantamount to election]] in November. He routed his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent, businesswoman Silvia Delamar, with almost 76% of the vote. The district was renumbered as the 3rd in 2006 and made even more Republican than its predecessor. Westmoreland was reelected five more times from this district with no substantive opposition.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe resides in [[Grantville, Georgia]], with his wife, Joan; they have three children and seven grandchildren.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://westmoreland.house.gov/ Congressman Lynn A. Westmoreland] official U.S. House site\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101028214437/http://www.lynnwestmoreland.org/ Lynn Westmoreland for Congress]\n* {{C-SPAN|Lynn Westmoreland}}\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Lynn_Westmoreland_%5BR-3%5D}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = w000796 | ballot = Lynn_Westmoreland | nndb = 311/000087050 | votesmart = 8001 | govtrack = 400627 | opencong = 400627 | rollcall = 20271 | politifact = lynn-westmoreland | fec = H4GA08067 | opensecrets = N00026163 | assets = lynn-westmoreland | legistorm = 530/Rep_Lynn_Westmoreland.html | followthemoney = 20614 | ontheissues = GA/Lynn_Westmoreland.htm | congress = lynn-westmoreland/1779 | worldcat = | cspan = 1013045 | imdb = 2292401 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAWE0KAP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mac Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Georgia|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Georgia's 8th congressional district]]|years=2005\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Mars